Group 14: Fatima Zohra Rouidi, Pelle Topper, Nina Lobo

 

Assignment 1: Canals

To find a route that is safe for the swimmers and does not have a big impact on the shipping in Amsterdam, we took various factors into account and selected a route by hand. We have incorporated all of these into a map and ultimately assessed which canals are the least harmful to swimmers while also causing minimal harm to the environment and commercial activity.

In the map below, you can see the results of our research.

 

 

 

Below, we will explain which factors we included and what our conclusion was:

Waterways

To start, we examined the waterways in the Amsterdam canals. Map 1 illustrates which water routes are utilized in Amsterdam and their levels of activity, as explained in Figure 2. In Figure 1, a more detailed chart shows the intersections and times when the waterways are busiest. Furthermore, we are aware that many tourist boats navigate Amsterdam, and we aim not to disrupt their activities. Using Map X, we can pinpoint the locations of these commercial boats.

Taking all of this into consideration, we concluded that the peak activity on the waterways begins around 11 o'clock. Therefore, it would be advisable to commence our swimming tour early and conclude it before this surge in traffic begins. Assuming an average person takes 2.5 hours to swim 5 kilometers, we have decided to start the swimming tour at 7 o'clock, allowing swimmers a four-hour window in case of emergency, late starts, and minimal likelihood of encountering boats.

 

 

Pollution

To ensure a healthy environment for the swimmers, we evaluated several water quality indicators. While there are a wide variety of factors to consider, our team prioritized the following:

        Low turbidity

        High oxygen content

        Low chloride content

        Avoid effluent points for treated sewage water

        Time and usage data for the canals

        Times and locations for touristic boat platforms along the canals

The first three indicators ensure better water quality for the participating swimmers. Lower turbidity translates to clearer water ideally less polluted.

Assignment 2: Tour Boats

1. How many of the canal boats currently in use are diesel/fossil fuel-driven and how
many boats are electric?

The Amsterdam canal cruise fleet contains 310 boats (2016) (TNO-2016-R10481.pdf). In 2020, 75% of the registered commercial vessels in Amsterdam were already electric (Amsterdam's boats go electric ahead of 2025 diesel ban | Reuters), which includes canal boats.

By 2025, the city is aiming for all commercial and residential boats to be emissions-free (Elektrisch varen - Gemeente Amsterdam). Because the swim takes place in 2024, additional boats must be electrified to reach the 2025 goal. By linear regression, we assume that at least 90% of the Amsterdam canal cruise fleet will be electric by mid-2024.

 

2. Are there peak times for the canal boats?

Depending on the canal,

Calculating with a cruise fleet of 310 boats the amount of energy needed per year is 9000 MWh. This is equivalent to 2.3 million liters diesel (TNO-2016-R10481.pdf). (make a comparison)

TNO-2016-R10481.pdf did calculate a business case about the costs of electrifying a canal cruise boat. Taking into account the fuel and energy price at that time and the financial losses due to the time that the boat is not in operation. Estimated is that the payback period in 2016 was 12 years. For 2024 it is estimated to be 6 years. We think it is feasible to make the transition and electrify the cruise boats.
